transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thanks for calling Viagra, Quinn speaking. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yes, I'd like to stop my prescription, please.

Speaker 1: Okay, let me pull up your account.

Speaker 2: Is your name William, Wilmer, excuse me?

Speaker 1: Wilmer, yeah, Wilmer.

Speaker 2: Alrighty, Wilmer, I do see you are a VIP here as well.

Speaker 1: Do you mind if I ask why you're canceling?

Speaker 2: Well, I didn't know I was going to get a monthly prescription.

Speaker 1: I thought I would just try it.

Speaker 2: Yeah, you don't have to get it monthly, sir.

Speaker 1: You can order as needed if that's better for you.

Speaker 2: Well, every month it seems like I'm getting a prescription coming in the mail.

Speaker 1: Yeah, you don't have to get it monthly, sir.

Speaker 2: You can choose when you get your deliveries,

Speaker 1: specifically the day and the month, or you can kind of just order as needed if that works better.

Speaker 2: Yeah, that's exactly what I want to do.

Speaker 1: All right, so basically we just keep your prescription open

Speaker 2: and your refills available to you for the next, like, six months,

Speaker 1: but you have to call in for your refills, okay?

Speaker 2: Okay, that sounds good.

Speaker 1: All righty.

Speaker 2: Now, what do you mean by keeping it open?

Speaker 1: You're not going to keep billing me every month, are you?

Speaker 2: No, no, no.

Speaker 1: Basically, we just keep your prescription open so you have refills to call in for

Speaker 2: because you can't get pills from a pharmacy without the prescription.

Speaker 1: All right.

Speaker 2: Okay, that sounds good.

Speaker 1: All righty.

Speaker 2: Well, I'll make that change for you now, sir.

Speaker 1: Thank you, sir.

Speaker 2: You're welcome.

Speaker 1: Bye.
